Overview

  • In this lecture, we will begin by explaining what a system is. We will examine how systems are categorized and how they have evolved over the years of automation. Then we will discuss how electronics have become part of systems and the consequent emergence of embedded systems.

  • We will then introduce the components of an embedded system and explain how each component contributes to the system. We will further discuss the typical layers of embedded software. We will conclude the lecture by exploring what a real-time operating system (RTOS) is and how it can be useful in a system.

    Learning Objectives

  • Understand the concepts of engineering systems and embedded systems.

  • Identify hardware and software components in an embedded system.

  • Describe the layers within embedded software.

  • Discuss the concept of an RTOS.

    What Is a System?

  • A system is a collection of components that are put together to perform a sequence of simple or complex operations. Multiple systems can also work together to create more complex systems.

  • Various types of systems have been developed over the periods of industrial and technological advancement of the past hundred years. These can be broadly categorized into five system types, as follows:

    • Purely mechanical (e.g., internal combustion engine)

    • Mechanical + electrical (e.g., traditional factory equipment)

    • Mechanical + electrical + electronic (e.g., Programmable Logic Controllers, or PLCs)

    • Electromechanical + precision control (e.g., Computer Numerical Control, or CNC)

    • Electromechanical + networking (e.g., Automated factories)

      Embedded systems (ESs)

  • Embedded systems (ESs) should, by right, be called embedded electronic systems, since they are mostly built with electronic components and are used to control mechanical or electromechanical systems. The embedded electronic systems are more commonly called “embedded systems”. Embedded systems could be broadly categorized as follows, based on their applications:

    • General purpose Ess: These systems are built to cater to a variety of

      applications and can be programmed to the application requirements.

    • Special purpose Ess: These systems are built for specific applications and are not easily reusable for other applications.

    • Networked Ess: These systems enable the networking of various ESs together to achieve application requirements, such as to control a group of machines in unison, like a modern production line.

      Control systems

  • ESs can also be categorized based on the nature of control they impose on the system. We call this a control system (see the following link for additional information on this topic: "Control

    theory" on Wikipedia). Control systems are generally divided into two distinct groups:

    • Open-loop systems

      Open-loop systems are systems that do not take the output of the system into account in determining subsequent operations of the system. These systems are usually manual or semi-automatic, where a certain amount of human interaction with the system is required.

    • Closed-loop systems

      In the case of closed-loop systems, the system is capable of obtaining feedback from the output and compensating for any errors detected in the output. These types of systems are usually automatic and need very little or no human interaction during their operation cycle.

      Exploring Embedded Systems

  • An electronic embedded system is a combination of hardware and software components.

  • In embedded systems, the hardware and the software work together to implement the required functionality of the system.

  • Depending on the type of application, the quantity of the hardware and the software in a system can vary.

    Hardware Components (1/2)

  • Hardware is usually a group of sensors, connected together to collect environmental information and share it with the software components of the system, which process this information and take required actions based on it.

  • The hardware components may also include input and output devices, to receive input from the user as well as share information with the user.

    Hardware Components (2/2)

  • Printed circuit board (PCB): A PCB is a board that holds the electronic components of the system together; it is also responsible for providing functionality such as connectivity between the electronic components, mechanical stability of the hardware, signal stability, and signal integrity, among other functions.

  • Electronic components mounted on the PCB: These components implement the required functionality of the system. They work in unison to achieve the required flow of control and other functions of the system.

  • Display system: The display system serves as an output device to display information to the user. The display system can range from a set of small LEDs to a large LCD display that can share a wealth of information.

  • Input devices: The input devices available on embedded systems are usually small keyboards or touch screens that allow the user to provide inputs to the system in order to obtain response and control the system’s behavior.

  • Central controller: In addition to the above components, embedded systems contain a central controller (a microcontroller or a microprocessor) that functions as the “brain” of the system and is responsible for its overall control, responding and reacting to any errors that may occur and tuning the system response per user settings and user input.

    Software Components

  • Similarly to the hardware components, the software components also need to work together to provide the required functionality expected by the user.

  • The software components run on the central controller.

  • The software serves as the layer between the user and the machine that the user is controlling.

  • The following are the software components typically found in embedded systems:

    • Driver software (or board support packages, BSPs)

    • Middleware software

    • Application software

      Driver software (or board support packages, BSPs)

  • The driver software is the lowest-level layer of the software component of an embedded system and is the layer that interacts with the hardware component directly.

  • This type of software is also called a low-level driver, since it is responsible for driving the hardware. It interacts with the hardware at the register level and is usually written in either the C programming language or an assembly language.

  • Typically this part of the software component is provided by the controller’s manufacturer and is never modified.

    Middleware software

  • Middleware software is responsible for the interaction between the driver and the higher-level application layer of the software component.

  • The middleware layer is more abstracted than the driver layer and thus offers more control to the user over how the system behaves.

  • One of the key middleware components is the operating system.

  • The operating system is akin to the “brain” of the software component and is responsible for controlling how the system behaves under various operating conditions.

  • It provides instructions to the other software components regarding which component should work when and how.

    Application software

  • Application software is the top layer of the software component and is the layer that directly interacts with the user.

  • This type of software is made to be user-friendly and is designed to provide great flexibility and usability to the user.

  • This layer also interacts with the middleware.

    Types of Operating Systems

  • Based on the user’s task response requirements, systems can be broadly divided into non-real-time and real-time systems.

    Non-Real-Time Systems

  • Systems that are not required to respond to a request from the user within a set amount of time are classified as non-real-time systems.

  • Examples of non-real-time systems are personal computers. Given a request from the user (e.g., copying a file from one location to another), the system is not required to complete the task within a specified amount of time, as this is not a time-critical task.

  • For systems like these, a Windows or Linux operating system would suffice. Also, these operating systems are large and require a considerable amount of memory space that is not usually available on embedded systems.

    Real-Time Systems (1/2)

  • A real-time system is a time-bound system which has well-defined, fixed time constraints. Processing must be performed within the defined time constraints, or the system will fail.

  • Such systems are either event-driven or time-sharing.

  • Event-driven systems switch between tasks based on their priorities (this is also referred to as preemptive scheduling), while time-sharing systems switch tasks based on clock interrupts. Most RTOSs use a preemptive scheduling algorithm.

  • If a real-time system fails to respond to a user request within the expected amount of time, this nonconformance can result in dangerous consequences.

  • An example of a real-time system is equipment used for medical applications, such as a drug delivery system. In this case, the system must continuously monitor its status and respond to the status within a specific amount of time to prevent any negative consequences to the patient.

    Real-Time Systems (2/2)

  • In systems like this, the operating system must prioritize the tasks occurring in the system and provide access to specific software control components to control the hardware.

  • Real-time systems have limited memory capacity, since they are small and need to be very cost-effective.

  • Therefore, operating systems built for these applications usually only have the features required for the specific type of hardware to which they are targeted, as well as a very small memory size.

    Real-Time Operating Systems (1/2)

  • A real-time operating system (RTOS) is an operating system (OS) intended to serve applications that process data in real time – i.e., as it comes in – typically without delays.

  • Processing time requirements (including any OS delays) are measured in tenths of seconds or even shorter time increments.

  • A key characteristic of an RTOS is the consistency of the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task.

  • The variability of task completion time (a.k.a. the jitter) in an RTOS is deterministic.

    Real-Time Operating Systems (2/2)

  • A ”hard” RTOS has a lower jitter than a “soft” RTOS. While a late response is acceptable in a soft RTOS, in a hard RTOS it is not acceptable.

  • An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft RTOS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically, it is a hard RTOS.

  • The principal design goal for RTOSs is not high throughput but rather a guaranteed latency of a performance category.

  • In other words, RTOSs are expected to have minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; an RTOS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.

    RTOS designs

  • An RTOS includes an advanced algorithm for scheduling tasks within the system. Scheduler flexibility enables a wider computer-system orchestration of various application priorities in the system, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a specific set of applications.

  • The most common RTOS designs are:

    • Event-driven

      Tasks are switched only when an event of higher priority needs servicing; this type of a switching algorithm is called preemptive or priority-based scheduling.

    • Time-sharing

      Tasks are switched on a regular clocked interrupt as well as on events;

      an example of a time-sharing switching algorithm is the round robin.

      Task: States

  • Time-sharing designs switch tasks more frequently than strictly required but provide smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or task has the sole use of the machine.

  • In an RTOS a task can be in one of three different states:

    • Running (executing on the CPU)

    • Ready (ready to be executed)

    • Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example)

  • Other states can be defined for tasks, but the above three are standard and usually sufficient for most RTOSs.

    Types of tasks

  • There are also different types of tasks that can be defined and used:

    • Periodic tasks

      These are tasks that need to be executed at regular intervals. Once such a task is completed, it returns to the Blocked state until the next time slot at which it needs to run.

    • Non-periodic tasks

      These are tasks executed on an as-needed basis, such as interrupt servicing. Once a task of this type is completed, it returns to the Blocked state until another event triggers that task.

    • Continuous tasks

      These are tasks that are executed non-stop. They are usually very low-priority tasks that allow other tasks to run.

      Scheduling algorithms

  • Various scheduling algorithms can be used by an RTOS scheduler. The following are some of the most commonly used algorithms:

    • Cooperative scheduling

    • Preemptive scheduling

    • Rate monotonic scheduling

    • Round robin scheduling

    • Fixed-priority preemptive scheduling

    • Static time scheduling

    • Earliest deadline first scheduling

      RTOS: Inter-Task Communication and Resource Sharin


  • Resource sharing and inter-task communication are maintained in an RTOS by using one or more of the following techniques:

    • Temporary masking or disabling of interrupts

    • Mutexes

    • Queues

    • Semaphores

  • These techniques will be explained in later chapters of this course

    RTOS: Memory Allocation

  • Memory allocation is critical in RTOS, since memory leaks could result in drastic performance failure, which is unacceptable for a realtime system. Memory allocation can be either dynamic or static.

  • Dynamic memory allocation must be handled well by the RTOS in order to avoid improper use of memory resources. The benefit of dynamic allocation, however, is greater flexibility for the application developer. Since the OS handles memory allocation, it is able to allocate and free memory as and when it is required and used.

  • Static memory allocation, on the other hand, gives the application developer more control over the allocation and deallocation of memory within the system.

    RTOS: Available RTOS Solutions

  • In the past, RTOSs were built by vendors specifically for their hardware requirements. Since most hardware was tailored to custom applications, the developers of these hardware devices differentiated between their devices and competitors’ devices by providing high-quality software interfaces and high-performance software. As a result, the RTOS played a crucial role in differentiating one product from another.

  • Since the RTOS was one of the major differentiators between product solutions offered by various companies, historically it was closed-source software that came with a license cost.

  • In recent times, however, hardware has become more widespread, and the difference between products now stems mostly from the custom application software that each product company builds.

  • For this reason, there are now various open-source RTOS offerings that

    developers can use with their hardware to build real-time systems.

    Closed- and Open-source RTOSs

  • Examples of both closed- and open-source RTOSs are listed below (arranged alphabetically):

    • Deos (DDC-I)

    • embOS (SEGGER)

    • FreeRTOS (Amazon)

    • Integrity (Green Hills Software)

    • Keil RTX (ARM)

    • LynxOS (Lynx Software Technologies)

    • MQX (Philips NXP / Freescale)

    • Nucleus (Mentor Graphics)

    • µC/OS (Micrium)

    • VxWorks (Wind River)

    • Zephyr (Linux Foundation)

    Operating Systems

  • The computers in embedded systems often do not interact directly with humans in the same way that desktop or handheld computers do.

  • As a consequence, the collection of services that they need from an operating system (OS) may be very different.

  • The dominant general-purpose OSs for desktops today, Microsoft Windows, Mac OS X, and Linux, provide services that may or may not be required in an embedded processor.

  • For example, many embedded applications do not require a graphical user interface (GUI), a file system, font management, or even a network stack.

    OSs for embedded applications

  • Several operating systems have been developed specifically for embedded applications, including Windows CE (WinCE) (from Microsoft), VxWorks (from Wind River Systems, acquired by Intel in 2009), QNX (from QNX Software Systems, acquired in 2010 by Research in Motion (RIM)), Embedded Linux (an open source community effort), and FreeRTOS (another open source community effort).

  • These share many features with general-purpose OSs, but typically have specialized the kernel to become a real-time operating system (RTOS).

  • An RTOS provides bounded latency on interrupt servicing and a scheduler for processes that takes into account real-time constraints.

    Mobile operating systems

  • Mobile operating systems are a third class of OS designed specifically for handheld devices.

  • The smart phone operating systems iOS (from Apple) and Android (from Google) dominate today, but there is a long history of such software for cell phones and PDAs.

  • Examples include Symbian OS (an open-source effort maintained by the Symbian Foundation), BlackBerry OS (from RIM), Palm OS (from Palm, Inc., acquired by Hewlett Packard in 2010), and Windows Mobile (from Microsoft).

  • These OSs have specialized support for wireless connectivity and media formats.

    The Kernel

  • The core of any operating system is the kernel, which controls the order in which processes are executed, how memory is used, and how information is communicated to peripheral devices and networks (via device drivers).

  • A microkernel is a very small operating system that provides only these services (or even a subset of these services).

  • OSs may provide many other services: could include user interface infrastructure (integral to Mac OS X and Windows), virtual memory, memory allocation and deallocation, memory protection (to isolate applications from the kernel and from each other), a file system, and services for programs to interact such as semaphores, mutexes, and message passing libraries.


    Embedded Operating Systems

    General Requirements

  • Except for very simple systems, I/O, scheduling, and context switching require the support of an operating system suited for embedded applications.

  • Context switching: Switching from the execution of one code object such that some other code object is executed.

  • Context switching multiplexes processors such that each code object seems to have its own processor.

  • For code objects, we distinguish between processes and threads.

  • A process is an executed program (or a part of a program) including memory content.

  • A thread is an executed program using the same address space as other programs.

    General Requirements

  • For processes, there is some form of memory protection, since processes cannot corrupt other process memory areas.

    • However, context switches have to change address translation information. Hence, they come with some overhead.

  • For threads, this protection does not exist.

    • In fact, threads sharing an address space will typically communicate via shared memory.

    • Context switching for threads is typically faster than for processes.

  • We do not need to distinguish between threads and processes if there is just one address space.

    Essential features of embedded operating systems

  • Operating systems have to provide communication and synchronization methods for threads and processes.

  • Due to the large variety of embedded systems, there is also a large variety of requirements for the functionality of embedded OSs.

  • Due to efficiency requirements, it is not possible to work with OSs which provide the union of all functionalities.

  • For most applications, the OS must be small. Hence, we need operating systems which can be flexibly tailored toward the application at hand.

  • Configurability is therefore one of the main characteristics of embedded OSs.

  • There are various techniques of implementing configurability, including

    Object orientation, and Aspect-oriented programming.

    Essential features of embedded operating systems

  • There is a large variety of peripheral devices employed in embedded systems.

  • Many embedded systems do not have a hard disk, a keyboard, a screen, or a mouse.

  • There is effectively no device that needs to be supported by all variants of the OS, except maybe the system timer.

  • Frequently, applications are designed to handle particular devices. In such cases, devices are not shared between applications, and hence there is no need to manage the devices by the OS.

  • Due to the large variety of devices, it would also be difficult to provide all required device drivers together with the OS. Hence, it makes sense to decouple OS and drivers by using special processes instead of integrating their drivers into the kernel of the OS.


    Embedded OS

    PCs

    Essential features of embedded operating systems

  • Protection mechanisms are sometimes not necessary, since embedded systems are sometimes designed for a single purpose (they are not supposed to support the so-called multiprogramming).

  • In contrast to desktop applications, it is possibly not always necessary to implement I/O instructions as privileged instructions and processes can sometimes be allowed to do their own I/O.


    Essential features of embedded operating systems

  • Interrupts can be connected to any thread or process.

  • Using OS service calls, we can request the OS to start or stop them if certain interrupts happen.

  • We could even store the start address of a thread or process in the interrupt vector address table, but this technique is very dangerous, since the OS would be unaware of the thread or process actually running.

  • Many embedded systems are real-time (RT) systems, and, hence, the OS used in these systems must be a real-time operating system (RTOS).

    Real-Time Operating Systems

  • “real-time operating system is an operating system that supports the construction of real-time systems”

    What is needed from an OS to be an RTOS?

  • There are four key requirements.

  1. The timing behavior of the OS must be predictable: For each service of the OS, an upper bound on the execution time must be guaranteed

  2. The OS must manage the scheduling of threads and processes: Scheduling can be defined as mapping from sets of threads or processes to intervals of execution time (including the mapping to start times as a special case) and to processors (in case of multiprocessor systems).

    What is needed from an OS to be an RTOS?

  3. Some systems require the OS to manage time: This management is mandatory if internal processing is linked to an absolute time in the physical environment.

    • Physical time is described by real numbers.

    • In computers, discrete time standards are typically used instead.

  4. The OS must be fast: An operating system meeting all the requirements mentioned so far would be useless if it were very slow.

    • Therefore, the OS must obviously be fast.

RTOSs categories

  • Fast proprietary kernels:“for complex systems, these kernels are inadequate, because they are designed to be fast, rather than to be predictable in every respect”.

    • Examples include QNX, PDOS, VCOS, VTRX32, and VxWorks.

  • Real-time extensions to standard OSs: In order to take advantage of comfortable mainstream operating systems, hybrid systems have been developed.

    • For such systems, there is an RT-kernel running all RT-processes. The standard operating

      system is then executed as one of these processes.

    • This approach has some advantages: for example, the system can be equipped with a standard OS API and can have graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and file systems.


      Embedded Linux

  • Increasing requirements to the functionality of embedded systems, such as Internet connectivity (in particular for the Internet of Things) or sophisticated graphics displays, demand that a large amount of software is added to a typical embedded system’s simple operating system.

  • It has been shown that it is possible to add some of this functionality to small embedded real-time operating systems, e.g., by integrating a small Internet protocol (IP) network stack.

  • However, integrating a number of different additional software components is a complex task and may lead to functional as well as security deficiencies.

    Embedded Linux

  • A different approach, enabled by the exponential growth of semiconductor densities according to Moore’s law, is the adaptation of a well-tested code base with the required functionality to run in an embedded context.

  • Here, Linux has become the OS of choice for a large number of complex embedded applications following this approach, such as Internet routers, GPS satellite navigation systems, network-attached storage devices, smart television sets, and mobile phones.

  • These applications benefit from easy portability—Linux has been ported to more than 30 processor architectures, including the popular embedded ARM, MIPS, RISC-V and PowerPC architectures—as well as the system’s open-source nature, which avoids the licensing costs arising for commercial embedded operating systems.

  • Adapting Linux to typical embedded environments poses a number of challenges due to its original design as a server and desktop OS.

    Real-Time Databases

  • Databases provide a convenient and structured way of storing and accessing information.

  • Accordingly, data bases provide an API for writing and reading information.

  • A sequence of read and write operations is called a transaction.

  • Transactions may have to be aborted for a variety of reasons: there could be hardware problems, deadlocks, problems with concurrency control, etc.

  • A frequent requirement is that transactions do not affect the state of the database unless they have been executed to their very end. Hence, changes caused by transactions are normally not considered to be final until they have been committed.

  • Most transactions are required to be atomic. This means that the end result (the new state of the database) generated by some transaction must be the same as if the transaction has been fully completed or not at all.

    Real-Time Databases

  • Also, the database state resulting from a transaction must be consistent.

  • Consistency requirements include, for example, that the values from read requests belonging to the same transaction are consistent (do not describe a state which never existed in the environment modeled by the database).

  • Furthermore, to some other user of the database, no intermediate state resulting from a partial execution of a transaction must be visible (the transactions must be performed as if they were executed in isolation).

  • Finally, the results of transactions should be persistent. This property is also called durability of the transactions. Together, the four properties printed in bold are known as ACID properties.

    Real-Time Databases

  • For some databases, there are soft real-time constraints.

    • For example, time constraints for airline reservation systems are soft.

  • In contrast, there may also be hard constraints.

    • For example, automatic recognition of pedestrians in automobile applications and target

      recognition in military applications must meet hard real-time constraints.

  • The above requirements make it very difficult to guarantee hard real-time constraints.

    • For example, transactions may be aborted various times before they are finally committed.

  • For all databases relying on demand paging and on hard disks, the access times to

    disks are hardly predictable.

  • Possible solutions include the main memory databases and predictable use of

    flash memory.

  • Embedded databases are sometimes small enough to make this approach

    feasible.

  • In other cases, it may be possible to relax the ACID requirements.

      What Is FreeRTOS?

  • FreeRTOS is one of the most commonly used real-time operating systems (RTOS) that is shared under the MIT open-source license.

  • FreeRTOS is an RTOS targeted toward microcontrollers and small microprocessors.

  • FreeRTOS includes a kernel and a growing set of IoT libraries suitable for use across all industry sectors.

  • FreeRTOS is built with an emphasis on reliability and ease of use.

  • In the next section, we will examine common technical, maintenance, and efficiency-related requirements for building embedded applications with FreeRTOS.

  • We will then identify some standard features of FreeRTOS.

    Application Requirements

  • FreeRTOS enables adopters to leverage various advantageous features of a real-time kernel, as compared to building a raw embedded application.

  • These features are typical requirements for most current embedded applications, since a single system may need to adapt to both simple and complex applications and should enable reuse of the system across varied application components.

    Technical Requirements

  • Modularity: is a key requirement for embedded system software, since this enables it to maintain software scalability (both upward and downward) without impacting the application’s features and functions.

  • Abstracting timing information: The timing requirements of the system must be understood and abstracted, so that they can be built into the controlling software’s environment.

  • Power management: Managing power in current embedded systems is another key factor. Because more and more applications require battery-powered operation, understanding power requirements and designing a proper approach for managing the power is important in building an efficient embedded system.

    Technical Requirements

  • Flexible interrupt management: The next step is to manage the various interrupts that are going to occur in the system. The interrupt requirements are based on the inputs that are part of the system. They need to be well-understood in order to create meaningful output based on the inputs.

  • Mixed processing requirements: Embedded systems are based on multiple types of inputs. Some are purely digital in nature, but there are also analogue inputs that need to be captured, processed, and understood in order to generate the required response to these inputs. An embedded system must be able to support mixed processing, so that it can handle various types of inputs.

  • System idle time management: The final consideration is how and when the system could potentially be idle and, during this idle time, what should be done within the system.

    Maintenance and Efficiency Requirement s

  • Testability: One of the key aspects in designing a system is the ability to maintain the system and fix any breakages quickly and efficiently. To support this requirement, it is essential to be able to test for any potential failures during the development of the system, as well as to reproduce any breakages identified during system operation. Therefore, when the system is designed, testability must be a built-in part of the design, including identifying what should be tested and how it needs to be tested.

  • Maintainability and extensibility: The system must be designed in a way that enables it to be maintained easily both on and off the field, from both the hardware and the software perspectives. Extensibility is also key; the system should be designed in a way that makes it simple to add features after the initial version of the system is completed.

    Maintenance and Efficiency Requirement s

  • Development of applications as a team: Complex applications are often developed by teams, and the design of the system must support the ability to do so quickly and effectively. For this reason, the system must be designed in a modular fashion, so that multiple individuals and even multiple teams can contribute to the development of components and modules of the application without negatively impacting existing components.

  • Code reuse: Where appropriate, code developed for one system should be available for reuse by other systems with similar functionality requirements. Designing the system in a modular fashion will support this requirement and thus increase the efficiency of building new applications.

  • Code efficiency: Finally, the code should be designed to make effective use of memory, and the developer must keep in mind the performance limitations of small controllers on which embedded systems are built.

    Features of FreeRTOS

  • The following are standard features of FreeRTOS (as adopted from the FreeRTOS Reference Manual):

    • Pre-emptive or cooperative operation

    • Highly flexible task priority assignment

    • Flexible, fast, and lightweight task notification mechanism

    • Queues

    • Binary semaphores

    • Counting semaphores

    • Mutexes

    • Recursive mutexes

    • Software timers

    • Event groups

    • Tick hook functions

    • Idle hook functions

    • Stack overflow checking

    • Trace recording

    • Task run-time statistics gathering

    • Optional commercial licensing and support

    • Full interrupt nesting model (for some architectures)

    • A tick-less capability for extremely low-power applications

    • Software-managed interrupt stack when appropriate (this can help save RAM)

      FreeRTOS Distribution Overview

  • FreeRTOS is distributed through a Git repository as a single compressed (ZIP) file with all the source code, so users can freely use it in their applications, as well as make any modifications to the code if required.

  • The distribution also contains demo applications and demos of ports to various controllers supported by FreeRTOS.

  • These demos help users of FreeRTOS to quickly adapt it to their requirements.

  • Many micro-controller suppliers deliver the RTOS as part of their tool suite, which further facilitates ease of development with FreeRTOS.

    Directory Structure of the FreeRTOS Distribution


  • The latest release of FreeRTOS can be downloaded from the FreeRTOS website. FreeRTOS is also hosted on GitHub and users can obtain the latest version of the source code from the Git location.

  • The folder structure of the FreeRTOS distribution is as follows (FreeRTOS top Release folder):


    Contents of the FreeRTOS Distribution

  • The core of the FreeRTOS kernel is contained in three files that reside in the FreeRTOS\FreeRTOS\Source subfolder.

  • These files are tasks.c, queue.c, and lists.c.

  • For simple applications, these three files are sufficient.

  • The Source folder contains the include subfolder, with include files required for setup.

  • There are other files that may be needed, depending on the specific functionality of a given application.

  • The Source directory also contains a subdirectory called portable, which contains

    subfolders with files specific to certain compilers and software tools.

  • The code found in these folders can be used as a starting point for creating ports per user requirements.

  • The Demo folder contains examples of applications ported to specific controllers.

  • Users planning to utilize a specific type of a controller can use one or more of the examples provided in this folder as a basis for building applications for their controller.


    Components of FreeRTOS and Their Applications

    Key Elements in FreeRTOS

  • The following are the key components of FreeRTOS:

    • Memory management

    • Tasks

    • Queues, semaphores, and mutexes

    • Direct task notifications

    • Stream and message buffers

    • Timers

  • Please note that there are also other components in FreeRTOS, which are not detailed in this course. These elements are required in more complex applications, and a thorough analysis of these can be found in the FreeRTOS user manual.

  • All features of FreeRTOS are controllable from the FreeRTOS configuration file, FreeRTOSConfig.h.

  • Each application needs to have this file as part of the system. This file contains configuration settings for enabling features of FreeRTOS required for the given application. A sample config file can be copied from the demo port that best fits the controller being used for that application.

    Memory Management: Memory Allocation Methods

  • Memory management is handled by FreeRTOS to enable efficient use of memory.

  • It supports both static and dynamic memory allocation. Both schemes have advantages and disadvantages, depending on the application.

  • The application developer chooses the appropriate memory management scheme based on

    the requirements. The same application can contain both dynamic and static allocation tasks.

  • FreeRTOS uses its own memory management methods and defines its own functions for memory allocation, as well as for the freeing of memory after use. It also defines multiple heap/memory management methods, which gives the user an option to select the optimal scheme that best fits their application.

  • The default memory allocation scheme in FreeRTOS is dynamic memory allocation.

  • In cases where the application developer requires more control over memory management for specific application components, the developer can choose to use static memory allocation for those tasks.

  • FreeRTOS provides a separate set of functions for components that need static memory allocation. These functions are available when configSUPPORT_STATIC_ALLOCATION is set to 1 in the configuration settings file.

    Advantages of using dynamic memory allocation

  • Fewer function parameters are required when an object is created.

  • The memory allocation occurs automatically, within the RTOS API functions.

  • The application developer does not need to concern themselves with allocating memory.

  • The RAM used by an RTOS object can be reused when the object is deleted, potentially reducing the application’s maximum RAM footprint.

  • RTOS API functions are provided to return information on heap usage, allowing the heap size to be optimized.

    Advantages of using static memory allocation

  • RTOS objects can be placed at specific memory locations.

  • The maximum RAM footprint can be determined at link time rather than at run-time.

  • The application developer does not need to concern themselves with graceful handling of memory allocation failures.

  • It allows the RTOS to be used in applications that simply don’t allow dynamic memory allocation (although FreeRTOS includes allocation schemes that can overcome most objections).

    Memory Management: Memory Management Schemes in FreeRTOS

  • FreeRTOS defines five memory management schemes.

  • They are contained in individual files in the source release: heap_1.c, heap_2.c, heap_3.c, heap_4.c, and heap_5.c, which are located

    in Source/Portable/MemMang directory.

  • Users can add their own implementations as required, but at least one of these implementations must be included when compiling the FreeRTOS source in the application.

    The five memory management schemes

  • heap_1.c

    heap_1 is the simplest implementation of memory management. It is similar to static memory allocation, so this solution may not be very useful in current implementations, since FreeRTOS now supports static allocation natively.

    However, it is very well-suited for most embedded systems, since they are small in memory usage and are deeply embedded. With this implementation, all of the required memory is always allocated at the start of the system’s execution and is only reallocated when the system is rebooted.

  • heap_2.c

    heap_2 uses a best-fit algorithm to allocate memory, and space that is no longer used is freed for further use. It does not combine free spaces into one block prior to reallocating. This scheme can be used when there is repeated deletion and creation of tasks or other RTOS components during the application’s execution. It is recommended not to use this scheme if the

    memory blocks that are being freed and reallocated are of random size, as this may result in memory fragmentation. Also, the allocation is not deterministic but is more efficient than C malloc implementations.

    The five memory management schemes

  • heap_4.c

    heap_4 uses a first fit algorithm to allocate memory. Unlike heap_2, it combines adjacent free spaces into a larger block and then assigns memory; it includes a coalescence algorithm that supports this capability. This scheme can be used in systems that require repeated creation and deletion of tasks and other components. Since this implementation combines memory regions into bigger memory blocks, it is less likely to result in improperly fragmented memory.

  • heap_5.c

    This scheme uses the same algorithms as heap_4 and additionally allows the heap to span multiple nonadjacent free regions of memory.

    Tasks

  • Tasks are the basic components of FreeRTOS.

  • They enable application developers to define specific pieces of functionality that need to be carried out at specific times during the execution of the application.

  • Any number of tasks can be defined inside of the application.

  • Tasks can be understood as small subprograms that are available for execution during the entire run-time of the main application.

    Tasks

  • The RTOS scheduler is responsible for controlling which task needs to be executed at any given time.

  • On single-core systems, only one task can be active in an application at any given point in time.

    • Therefore, the scheduler is also responsible for safely enabling and disabling each task, as well as for saving state, so that each task is brought back to its prior state when re-enabled.

  • This is achieved by the FreeRTOS scheduler via maintaining an individual stack for each task.

    Tasks: States

  • A task can exist in one of the following four states:

    • Ready: In this state, the task is ready to run; i.e., it is not in a Blocked or Suspended state. However, it is not running because another higher or equal priority task is already running on the processor.

    • Running: In this state the task is being executed on the processor. If the system has only one core, then there can only be one task running at any given point in time.

    • Blocked: In this state, the task is not ready to run because it is awaiting inputs from external sources, other tasks, or temporal events (such as timer events or delay events). There is an associated timeout for each Blocked task, and once this timeout is reached, the task will move out of the Blocked state and into the Ready state. After the timeout, the task does not need to wait for the event that was blocking it to occur.

    • Suspended: Suspended tasks cannot automatically come out of this state, as there is no associated timeout. They must be explicitly brought out of the Suspended state by the application via a resume operation.

      Tasks: Priorities

  • Tasks can be assigned priorities as required.

  • FreeRTOS allows the user to define a variable number of priority levels.

  • The levels start with 0, and the maximum level is defined in the FreeRTOSConfig.h file.

    • This maximum should be set to a reasonable number in order to minimize RAM usage.

  • The scheduling of the tasks is handled by the scheduler.

  • The scheduler ensures that Ready-state tasks of higher priority are

    executed before lower-priority tasks that are also in the Ready state.

  • FreeRTOS can be configured to run tasks of equal priority in a time slice manner, by setting configUSE_TIME_SLICING in the config file.

  • The slicing between the tasks with equal priority is managed using a round robin arbitration scheme.

    Tasks: Implementation

  • Tasks are created

    using either xTaskCreate() or xTaskCreateStatic() functio n and can be deleted using the xTaskDelete() function.

  • Parameters can be passed into the task, for further processing, using the parameters pointer.

    Sample task implementation structure

  • Step 1: Create two tasks:

    xTaskCreate( prvQueueReceiveTask, "Rx", configMINIMAL_STACK_SIZE * 2U, NULL, mainQUEUE_RECEIVE_TASK_PRIORITY, NULL );


    xTaskCreate( prvQueueSendTask, "Tx", configMINIMAL_STACK_SIZE * 2U, NULL, mainQUEUE_SEND_TASK_PRIORITY, NULL );

    Sample task implementation structure

  • Step 2: Define Task 1 (prvQueueReceiveTask)

    static void prvQueueReceiveTask( void *pvParameters )

    {

    unsigned long ulReceivedValue;

    const unsigned long ulExpectedValue = 100UL; const char * const pcMessage1 = "Blink1"; const char * const pcMessage2 = "Blink2"; const char * const pcFailMessage = "Unexpected

    value received\r\n";

    int f = 1;

    /* Remove compiler warning about unused parameter.

    */

    ( void ) pvParameters;

    for( ;; )

    {....

    Queues

  • Queues are the basic inter-task communication mechanism.

  • Tasks can use them to share information with other tasks.

  • The queues are implemented as thread safe FIFOs.

  • Tasks push information to the back of the queue, and other tasks that need to consume the

    enqueued data pull it off the queue and process it.

  • When required, it is also possible for tasks to push data to the front of the queue rather than to the back.

  • FreeRTOS uses a queue by copy method, where the data sent to the queue is copied into the

    queue.

    • This method results in a simple but powerful implementation.

  • Data can be shared through the queue in one of the following formats:

    • Raw data

    • Reference to data through pointers (when the data that needs to be shared is significant in size)

  • FreeRTOS is responsible for allocating memory for the queue and for storing the data as required.

    Queues: Access from Multiple Tasks

  • Queues can have multiple tasks writing to them or reading from them.

  • It is common to have multiple tasks writing to a queue and less common to have multiple tasks reading from it.

    Queues: Blocking and Unblocking Mechanism

  • When a task attempts to read from an empty queue, the task will be placed into the Blocked state until either data becomes available on the queue or the block timeout is reached.

  • When a task attempts to write to a full queue, the task will be placed into the Blocked state until either space becomes available on the queue or the block timeout is reached.

  • Tasks that are blocked do not consume CPU time, so other tasks can run.

  • If more than one task blocks on the same queue, then the task with the highest priority will be the task that is unblocked first.

    Queues: Implementation

  • The following example shows how queues can be implemented and used between two tasks.

  • Step 1: Create a queue

    /* Create the queue. */

    xQueue = xQueueCreate( mainQUEUE_LENGTH, sizeof( uint32_t ) );

  • Step 2: Use the queue

    /* Send a value to the queue, causing the task receiving

    this data from the queue to unblock and toggle the LED.

    0 is used as the block time so that the sending operation will not block; it shouldn't need to block, as the queue should always be empty at this point in the code. */

    xQueueSend( xQueue, &ulValueToSend, 0U );

    Semaphores and Mutexes

  • Aside from queues, FreeRTOS has semaphores and mutexes that can be used for inter-task communication based on application requirements.

  • More details on semaphores and mutexes in FreeRTOS are explained in the FreeRTOS Tutorial Book.

    Direct Task Notifications

  • Direct task notifications are events sent directly to a task without an intermediate mechanism like a queue or a semaphore.

  • This makes the communication faster and occupies far less memory space.

  • The task is blocked when there is a notification bit set in the notification event array.

  • Only one notification can block the task at a time; if another event were to occur, it would not affect the state of the task.

    Stream and Message Buffers

  • Stream buffers offer a one-to-one communication mechanism in the following cases:

    1. Task-to-task communication or

    2. Interrupt-to-task communication

  • These buffers are optimized for single write, single read scenarios. Stream buffers are capable of streaming bytes, and message buffers are capable of passing variable-sized discrete messages. Message buffers are built on top of stream buffers.

  • These buffers are very useful for the following types of communication scenarios:

    • Passing data from an interrupt service routine to a task.

    • Passing data from one microcontroller core to another on dual-core CPUs.

  • The data is passed via copy; i.e., the data is copied into the buffer by the sender and out of the buffer by the read operation.

    Timers

  • Timers can be implemented in software in an RTOS, so they can also be called software timers.

  • They do not use a hardware resource and do not consume CPU time.

  • A timer enables one to trigger tasks or events that need to occur at some point in the future.

  • The future time of execution is controlled by the timer settings. The task to be executed is called the timer’s callback function.

    • The timer’s callback function is executed once the timer – or the timer’s period – expires.

  • Like other RTOS components, a timer must be explicitly created before it can be used.

    Timers: Efficiency Considerations in Software Timer Implementations

  • Software timer functionality is, in general, easy to implement, but it is difficult to implement efficiently.

  • The RTOS implementation of a timer has the following properties:

    1. Does not execute timer callback functions from an interrupt context until the timer has actually expired.

    2. Does not consume any processing time.

    3. Does not add any processing overhead to the tick interrupt.

    4. Does not perform other memory access operations while interrupts are disabled.

  • The timer service task primarily makes use of existing FreeRTOS features, allowing timer functionality to be added to an application with minimal impact on the size of the application.

    Timers: Important Information on Writing Timer Callback Functions

  • Timer callback functions execute in the context of the timer service task. It is therefore essential that timer callback functions never attempt to block.

  • For example, a timer callback function must not

    call vTaskDelay() or vTaskDelayUntil(), nor should it specify a non-zero block time when accessing a queue or a semaphore.

    Timers: Types of Timers

  • Two types of timers can be defined and used in an application.

  • One-shot timers: A one-shot timer is executed only once.

    • Once the timer expires, its callback is called and executed once.

  • Auto-reload timers: An auto-reload timer keeps executing indefinitely, as long as the application is running.

    • Every time the timer expires, the callback is executed, and the timer is reset; the timer runs again until the next time it expires, causing the callback to be executed.

    • This process continues to repeat, resulting in a periodic execution of the callback.

      RISC-V Processors


      Lecture 7– Part I

      Learning Objectives

  • By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

    • Understand RISC-V terminology.

    • Follow the RISC-V instruction set.

    • Use RISC-V processors.

    • Use RISC-V tools to build simple applications.

      What Is RISC-V?

  • RISC-V is a new Instruction Set Architecture (ISA) that was originally defined in support of education and research in the field of Computer Architecture but has now grown into a free standard and open architecture that the industry has adopted to build its own processors.

    Goals for defining RISC-V

  • The following are the goals for defining RISC-V, as defined in the RISC-V specifications.

  • The specific document that enumerates these goals is the Technical Report UCB/EECS-2014-54.

    • A completely open ISA that is freely available to academia and industry.

    • A real ISA suitable for direct native hardware implementation, not just simulation or binary translation.

    • An ISA that avoids “over-architecting” for a particular microarchitecture style (e.g., microcoded, in-order, decoupled, out-of-order) or implementation technology (e.g., full-custom, ASIC, FPGA), but which allows efficient implementation in any of these.

    • An ISA separated into a small base integer ISA, usable by itself as a base for customized accelerators or for educational purposes, and optional standard extensions, to support general-purpose software development.

    • Support for the revised 2008 IEEE-754 floating-point standard.

    • An ISA supporting extensive user-level ISA extensions and specialized variants.

    • Both 32-bit and 64-bit address space variants for applications, operating system kernels, and hardware implementations.

    • An ISA with support for highly-parallel multicore or manycore implementations, including heterogeneous multiprocessors.

    • Optional variable-length instructions to both expand available instruction encoding space and to support an optional dense instruction encoding for improved performance, static code size, and energy efficiency.

    • A fully virtualizable ISA to ease hypervisor development.

    • An ISA that simplifies experiments with new supervisor-level and hypervisor-level ISA designs.

      RISC-V ISA

  • The specification avoids defining implementation details as much as possible; therefore, it can be seen as a software-visible interface to a wide variety of hardware implementations, rather than catering to a specific hardware implementation.

  • The specification is divided into two volumes – one that defines the “base unprivileged” instructions and one that defines the “classic privileged” features of RISC-V.

  • In the following slides, a basic insight into the design of an unprivileged ISA is provided, and you can refer to the privileged specifications as required.

    RISC-V Hardware Platform Terminology

  • A RISC-V hardware platform can contain one or more RISC-V-compatible processing cores, together with other (non-RISC-V-compatible) cores, fixed-function accelerators, various physical memory structures, I/O devices, and an interconnect structure that allows the components to communicate.

  • A component is termed a core if it contains an independent instruction fetch unit.

  • A RISC-V-compatible core might support multiple RISC-V-compatible hardware threads (or harts), through multithreading.

  • A RISC-V core may have additional specialized instruction-set extensions or an

    added coprocessor.

  • The term coprocessor is used to refer to a unit that is attached to a RISC-V core and is mostly sequenced by a RISC-V instruction stream, but which contains additional architectural state and instruction-set extensions and possibly has some limited autonomy relative to the primary RISC-V instruction stream.

    RISC-V Hardware Platform Terminology

  • The term accelerator refers to either a non-programmable fixed-function unit or a core that can operate autonomously but is specialized for certain tasks. In RISC-V systems, there may be many programmable accelerators that are RISC-V-based cores with specialized instruction-set extensions and/or customized coprocessors. I/O accelerators are an important class of RISC-V accelerators; they offload I/O processing tasks from the main application cores.

  • The system-level structure of a RISC-V hardware platform can range from a single-core microcontroller to a many-thousand-node cluster of shared-memory, multi-core server nodes.

  • Even small systems on a chip might be structured as a hierarchy of multicomputers and/or multiprocessors, to modularize development effort or to provide secure isolation between subsystems.

  • For more information refer to the RISC-V specifications.

    RISC-V Software Execution Environments and Harts


  • The execution environment on which a RISC-V program runs determines how it behaves.

  • The Execution Environment Interface (EEI) of RISC-V defines the initial state of the program, as well as the number and type of harts that the environment can handle, including the privilege modes supported by the harts.

  • The EEI also defines the accessibility and attributes of memory and I/O regions, how each hart behaves for all legal instructions executed on it (i.e., the ISA is one component of the EEI), and the handling of any interrupts or exceptions raised during execution, including environment calls.

  • Examples of EEIs include the Linux application binary interface (ABI) and the

    RISC-V supervisor binary interface (SBI).

  • The RISC-V execution environment can be implemented as pure hardware, as pure software, or as a combination of hardware and software.

  • For example, opcode traps and software emulation can be used to implement functionality not provided in the hardware.

    Examples of Execution Environment Implementations


  • “Bare metal” hardware platforms, where harts are directly implemented by physical processor threads and instructions have full access to the physical address space.

    • In this implementation, the hardware platform defines an execution environment

      that begins at power-on reset.

  • RISC-V operating systems that provide multiple user-level execution environments.

    • In this model, the environments are provided by multiplexing user-level harts onto available physical processor threads and by controlling access to memory via virtual memory.

  • RISC-V hypervisors that provide multiple supervisor-level execution environments for guest operating systems.

  • RISC-V emulators, such as Spike, QEMU, or rv8.

    • These emulate RISC-V harts on an underlying x86 system and can provide either a

      user-level or a supervisor-level execution environment.

      RISC-V: Technical capabilities and features



      RISC-V ISA

      Overview

  • The RISC-V ISA is divided into two parts.

  • One part is the base integer ISA that all implementations of the processor must support.

  • The second part is the additional set of instructions that can be supported as extended instructions.

  • The support for extended instructions is optional.

    Base Integer ISA

  • The base is restricted to the minimum set of instructions sufficient to support existing compilers, assemblers, linkers, and operating systems (with additional privileged instructions). Therefore, the base provides a simple and convenient starting point for building custom processors, with additional specialized ISAs as required.

  • There are actually four base ISAs which form the RISC-V ISA family.

    • These are categorized based on the width of the integer registers, the corresponding

      address width, and the number of integer registers.

  • The following are the ISAs defined as part of the RISC-V ISA family:

    • RV32I – Primary ISA, 32 bit address capable (XLEN=32)

    • RV64I – Primary ISA, 64 bit address capable (XLEN=64)

    • RV32E – Subset of RV32I, defined to suit small micro-controllers, with half the number of registers

    • RV128I – Future ISA to support 128-bit addressing (XLEN=128)


      The term XLEN to refer to the width of an integer register in bits.

      Why multiple ISA variants?

  • The decision to have multiple ISA variants and not make RV32I a strict subset of RV64I is rooted in several design considerations:

  1. Scalability and Resource Constraints

    • RV32I and RV64I refer to the base integer instruction sets with 32-bit and 64-bit word sizes, respectively.

    • In some embedded systems or applications with resource constraints, a 32-bit architecture might be preferred to save space and

      power.

  2. Efficiency and Performance

    • RV64I supports 64-bit data paths, which can be beneficial for applications that require larger address spaces and operations on 64-bit data.

    • RV32I is more efficient in terms of code density and may be preferable for applications with smaller memory footprints.

  3. Compatibility with Existing Software

    • RV32I and RV64I maintain compatibility with existing software libraries and tools designed for 32-bit and 64-bit architectures,

      respectively.

    • This allows for a smoother transition and facilitates reuse of software components.

  4. Diversity of Applications

    • RISC-V's modular design allows for the addition of optional extensions to the base ISA to tailor the architecture for specific applications.

    • Different applications may have diverse requirements, and the flexibility of RISC-V allows designers to choose the most suitable

      configuration.

  5. Design Philosophy

    • The RISC-V design philosophy emphasizes simplicity and modularity. By allowing variations in the base ISA, designers have the freedom to select the configuration that best suits their needs.

Encoding Spaces

  • The ISA has been designed for extensive customization and specialization. Each specific ISA has been defined in such a way that it can be extended with one or more instructions, as required.

  • RISC-V instruction-set encoding space and related encoding spaces, such as the Control and Status Registers (CSRs), are divided into three disjoint categories:

    • Standard encodings are defined by the Foundation and shall not conflict with other standard extensions for the same base ISA.

    • Reserved encodings are currently not defined but are saved for future standard extensions.

    • Custom encodings are made available for vendor-specific, non-standard extensions and shall never be used for standard extensions. Non-standard extensions are not defined by the Foundation.

      List of ISAs

  • The following is the list of ISAs as defined by the base ISA specifications.

    • I – Base Integer ISA

    • M – Standard Integer Multiply and Divide Extensions

    • A – Standard Integer Atomic Extensions (atomically read, modify, and write memory for synchronization)

    • F – Floating-Point Registers (single-precision computational instructions,

      loads, and stores)

    • D – Double-Precision Floating-Point Registers (double-precision computational instructions, loads, and stores)

    • C – Compressed Instructions (provide narrower 16-bit instruction versions of

      the base instructions)

      RISC-V Instructions Formats

  • These are the 32-bit RISC-V instruction formats:


    RV32I Base Integer Instructions



    RV64 Extensions


    Fields

  • opcode (7 bits): Partially specifies one of the 6 types of instruction formats.

  • funct7 and funct3 (10 bits): In combination further specify the operation to be performed.

  • rs1 (5 bits): Specifies, by index, the source register containing the first operand.

  • rs2 (5 bits): Specifies the source register containing the second operand.

  • rd (5 bits): Specifies the destination register to which the computation result will be directed.

  • The RISC-V ISA defines the required set of registers that need to be implemented on the processor, so that software across all implementations sees the same processor register set.

    Memory (1/3)

  • A RISC-V hart has a single, byte-addressable address space of 2XLEN bytes for all memory accesses, where XLEN is the width of the instruction (e.g., for RV32, XLEN is 32).

  • A word of memory is defined as 32 bits (4 bytes). Correspondingly, a halfword is 16 bits (2 bytes), a doubleword is 64 bits (8 bytes), and a quadword is 128 bits (16 bytes).

  • The memory address space is circular; hence, the byte at address 2XLEN−1 is adjacent to the byte at address zero. Accordingly, memory address computations performed by the hardware ignore overflow and instead wrap around to modulo 2XLEN.

  • The execution environment determines the mapping of hardware resources into a hart’s address space. Different address ranges of a hart’s address space may (1) be vacant, (2) contain main memory, or (3) contain one or more I/O devices.

  • Reads and writes of I/O devices may have visible side-effects, but accesses to main memory cannot. Although it is possible for the execution environment to call everything in a hart’s address space an I/O device, it is usually expected that some portion will be specified as main memory.

  • When the processor has more than one hart, (1) the address space could be unique for each of the harts, (2) it could be the same for both harts, or (3) some portions could be common and other portions unique to each of them.

    Memory (2/3)

  • Executing each machine instruction on RISC-V results in one or more explicit or

    implicit memory accesses.

  • For each executed instruction, there is at least one implicit memory access; this is the instruction’s fetch operation, which instructs the processor on what needs to be executed.

  • A number of RISC-V instructions do not require any additional implicit memory accesses aside from the fetch, as all of the information required for the processor to perform the operation is encoded in the fetch.

  • There are also specific load and store instructions that perform explicit memory

    access, accessing the required location as part of the instruction.

  • The execution environment determines which part of the memory is accessible for which type of memory access. Based on this determination, some portions of the memory cannot be accessed by a specific operation, and any attempt to access those locations would result in the processor raising an exception for that instruction.

  • Vacant spaces in the address space are never accessible.

    Memory (3/3)

  • The memory consistency model defines the order in which memory operations (reads and writes) appear to be executed with respect to each other in a multithreaded or multiprocessor system.

  • The default memory consistency model for RISC-V is the RISC-V Weak Memory Ordering (RVWMO). This model is defined as part of

    the specifications.

  • "Weak Memory Ordering" means that the order in which memory operations are observed by different threads may not strictly follow the order in which they are executed in the program. There can be reordering of memory operations to optimize performance, but certain constraints and guarantees are still maintained.

  • An alternate strong model is also defined in the specifications, and an implementation could choose to support this ordering model instead of the weak memory model.

    RISC-V RVWMO: Example (1/2)

  • Let's consider a simple example to illustrate the concept of weak memory ordering in the context of RISC-V RVWMO. Assume we have two threads, T1 and T2, running on a dual-core RISC-V processor.

  • Suppose we have the following code snippets for each thread:

    # Thread T1

    LW

    R1, 0(R2)

    #

    Load

    SW

    R3, 4(R4)

    #

    Store

    # Thread T2

    LW

    R5, 4(R6)

    #

    Load

    SW

    R7, 0(R8)

    #

    Store

    In a strongly ordered memory model, the loads and stores from different threads would always be observed in the same order they are executed.

    However, in a weakly ordered model like RVWMO, there

    can be some reordering for optimization purposes.

    RISC-V RVWMO: Example (2/2)

  • Let's consider a possible reordering of the above instructions due to weak memory ordering:

    # Possible Weak Memory Ordering

    LW

    R1,

    0(R2)

    #

    Load

    LW

    R5,

    4(R6)

    #

    Load

    SW

    R7,

    0(R8)

    #

    Store

    SW

    R3,

    4(R4)

    #

    Store

    # Execution order may be different from program order


    In this example, the loads and stores from different threads are reordered. This reordering might be done by the processor for performance reasons, but RVWMO ensures that certain dependencies are still maintained. For instance, the store in T2 is not observed before the load in T2, preserving the integrity of the program's logic.


    This demonstrates the flexibility allowed by weak memory ordering, where the order of memory operations can be adjusted for performance, as long as certain essential constraints are preserved.

    Instruction Length Encoding

  • The instruction length of the base instructions of RISC-V is 32 bits. The standard length encoding scheme is, however, designed to support variable length encoding of the instruction.

  • Extended instructions can contain any number of 16-bit parcels aligned to the 16-bit boundary.

  • The standard compressed ISA provides a compressed form of the instructions that is 16-bit wide and can result in reduction of code size.

  • This also relaxes the alignment constraints of the instructions and enables alignment of all instructions at the 16-bit boundary (for both 16-bit and 32-bit instructions), resulting in improved code density.

  • More details on variable-length encoding of the ISA can be obtained from the RISC-V base specifications.

    Exceptions, Interrupts, and Traps Explained

  • Exceptions are unusual conditions, associated with an instruction in the current RISC-V hart, that may occur at runtime.

    • Example: Division by zero. If a program attempts to divide a number by

      zero, a divide-by-zero exception may be triggered.

  • Interrupts are external asynchronous events that may cause a RISC-V hart to experience an unexpected transfer of control.

    • Example: Timer interrupt. An external timer may generate an interrupt to signal that a specific time period has elapsed, requiring the processor's attention to handle the timer event.

  • Traps refer to the transfer of control to a trap handler, caused by either an exception or an interrupt.

    Scenarios that can lead to traps in RISC-V

  • Page Fault: When a program attempts to access a memory page that is not currently in physical memory (page fault), it can lead to a trap. The operating system's page fault handler is then invoked to bring the required page into memory.

  • Illegal Instruction: If the processor encounters an instruction that is not a valid instruction for the current ISA, it can trigger an illegal instruction trap. This could occur, for example, if an application is trying to execute data as code.

  • Privileged Instruction: Certain instructions are privileged and can only be executed in a higher privilege level, typically by the operating system. If a user-level program attempts to execute a privileged instruction, it results in a trap, and control is transferred to the operating system.

  • Memory Protection Violation: Attempts to access restricted memory regions or perform unauthorized memory operations can result in a memory protection violation trap. The operating system can then handle the violation, possibly terminating the offending process.

  • Floating-Point Exceptions: Involves traps caused by exceptional conditions during floating-point arithmetic operations, such as division by zero, overflow, or invalid operations. The processor can trap to a floating-point exception handler to handle these situations.

  • Debug Traps: Debugging features in RISC-V processors may include breakpoints or watchpoints. When a program reaches a breakpoint or accesses a watched memory location, a debug trap can occur, transferring control to a debugging handler.

  • External Hardware Interrupts: In addition to interrupts from timers, other external hardware events, such as I/O device signals or communication events, can trigger traps. The operating system or application can handle these traps to respond to external events.

    Unspecified Behaviors and Values

  • The specification and the architecture fully describe what the implementations must do, as well as any constraints on what they may do. When the architecture does not explicitly define a behavior, then this behavior is defined as UNSPECIFIED.

  • UNSPECIFIED behaviors or values are intentionally left unconstrained, so that they may be defined in extensions, platform standards, or other implementations. In addition, if there are unconstrained definitions, they also must be defined as UNSPECIFIED. These values can be further extended or defined later as required.

  • Refer to the RISC-V reference card for the list of instructions in the RISC-V ISA and the related extensions of the base ISA.

    RISC-V Processor Market Offerings

  • There is a rapidly growing ecosystem for RISC-V processors. Both open-source and commercial offerings of RISC-V processors are available. A list of available processors can be found on GitHub.

  • Aside from the list of cores available for use, there are also ready-made chips and systems on a chip (SoCs) that are built around RISC-V processors. Various large chip companies like NVIDIA and Western Digital have used RISC-V in their product offerings.

  • Additionally, development boards built using the RISC-V processors are being planned at the time of creation of this course.
